'''Granule cell dispersion''' is one of the abnormal structural changes that has been shown in brains of patients with [[temporal lobe epilepsy]]. It has also been shown in different animal models, such as the [[kainic acid]] model,<ref name="Murphy BL 1">{{cite journal|last=Murphy|first=Brian L|author2=Rylon D. Hofacer |author3=Christian N Faulkner |author4=Andreas W Loepke |author5=Steve C Danzer |title=Abnormalities of granule cell dendritic structure are a prominent feature of the intrahippocampal kainic acid model of epilepsy despite reduced post-injury neurogenesis|journal=Epilepsia|date=May 2012|volume=53|issue=5|pages=908–921|doi=10.1111/j.1528-1167.2012.03463.x|pmid=22533643 |pmc=3340618}}</ref> [[pilocarpine]] model,<ref name="Mello LE (1)">{{cite journal|last=Mello|first=L |author2=Cavalheiro, E. |author3=Tan, A. |author4=Pretorius, J. |author5=Babb, T. |author6=Finch, D.|title=Granule cell dispersion in relation to mossy fiber sprouting, hippocampal cell loss, silent period and seizure frequency in the pilocarpine model of epilepsy|journal=Epilepsy resesarch|year=1992|volume=9|pages=51–60|pmid=1285914}}</ref> and [[kindling model]]. But granule cell dispersion was not found by using perforant pathway stimulation.<ref name="Sloviter 1">{{cite journal|last=Sloviter|first=Robert S|author2=Friederike Kienzler |author3=Braxton A. Norwood |title=Hippocampal injury, atrophy, synaptic reorganization, and epileptogenesis after perforant pathway stimulation-induced status epilepticus in the mouse|journal=Journal of Comparative Neurology|date=10 July 2009|volume=515|issue=2|pages=181–196|doi=10.1002/cne.22059|pmid=19412934|pmc=2705826}}</ref>
It was first described by Houser.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Houser|first=Carolyn R|title=Granule cell dispersion in the dentate gyrus of humans with temporal lobe epilepsy.|journal=Brain Research|date=December 1990|volume=535|issue=2|pages=195–204|pmid=1705855|doi=10.1016/0006-8993(90)91601-c}}</ref> In a normal situation, the granule cells in [[dentate gyrus]] should be tightly packed. But in granule cell dispersion, the compact formation was lost, and the axons need to extend longer to reach the neighboring granule cells.
==Mechanism of formation== There are currently two hypotheses for the mechanism. It might be a consequence of a migration disorder, and the first hypothesis considers an initial injury that release toxin(s) that affect the normal [[migration of granule cells]]. The second hypothesis concerns the role of reelin (see below).
===Reelin role in temporal lobe epilepsy=== [[Reelin]] is required for normal neuronal lamination humans, and the lack of this expression can lead to migration defect associated with temporal lobe epilepsy<ref name="Haas 1">{{cite journal|last=Hass|first=Carola A|author2=Oliver Dudeck |author3=Matthias Kirsch |author4=Csaba Huszka |author5=Gunda Kann |author6=Stefan Pollak |author7=Josef Zentner |author8=Michael Frotscher |title=Role for Reelin in the Development of Granule Cell Dispersion in Temporal Lobe Epilepsy|journal=The Journal of Neuroscience|date=15 July 2002|volume=22|issue=14|pages=5797–5802|pmid=12122039}}</ref>
