'''Stentato''' or '''stentando''' (the past participle and gerund of the [[Italian (language)|Italian]] verb ''[[wikt:stentare|stentare]]'' "to find it hard to do something, to have difficulty doing something") is a [[musical expression]] which means "labored, heavy, in a dragging manner, sluggish", or "strong and forced".<ref>[http://dictionary.onmusic.org/terms/3344-stentando OnMusic Dictionary]</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=The Encyclopedia Americana: A Library of Universal Knowledge |last= |first= |year=1919 |publisher=Encyclopedia Americana Corp. |volume=v. 19 |page=644}}</ref>  It is abbreviated "sten." or "stent." and is, for example, the direction given for the last 17 bars of the Sanctus of [[Giuseppe Verdi]]'s [[Requiem (Verdi)|Requiem]] and also used by [[Ottorino Respighi]] in his composition [[Pini di Roma]].

